<section xml:id="section-factoring">
  <title>Factoring</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      You might already know how to multiply polynomials. That's the process where you start with
      something like <m>(x+2)(x+3)</m> and end up with <m>x^2+5x+6</m>. This section is about the
      <em>opposite</em> process. We start with something like <m>x^2+5x+6</m> and we need to reverse
      engineer that it comes from <m>(x+2)(x+3)</m>. This is called <term>factoring</term>.
    </p>

    <!-- <figure>
      <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
      <video youtubeplaylist="PLfPh0EsBc0yIIJk5TgiNzpTktexDYGi_h"/>
    </figure> -->
  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Motivation for Factoring</title>
    <p>
      When you write <m>x^2+2x</m>, you have an algebraic expression built with two
      <term>terms</term><mdash/>two parts that are <em>added</em> together. When you write
      <m>x(x+2)</m>, you have an algebraic expression built with two <term>factors</term><mdash/>two
      parts that are <em>multiplied</em> together. Factoring is useful, because sometimes having
      parts that are <em>multiplied</em> together makes it easy to answer a bigger question.
    </p>
    <p>
      You've seen this with fractions. If you have <m>\frac{133}{171}</m>, it looks like an
      intimidating fraction. But if we break things down into pieces multiplied together:
      <m>\frac{7\cdot19}{9\cdot19}</m>. Now you can see that the factors of <m>19</m> cancel. We
      actually have a less intimidating fraction to work with: <m>\frac79</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There are more reasons to learn and appreciate factoring. One of them is that there is a
      relationship between a factored polynomial function and the horizontal intercepts of its
      graph. For example in the graph of <m>f</m> where <m>f(x)=(x+2)(x-3)</m>, the horizontal
      intercepts are <m>(-2,0)</m> and <m>(3,0)</m>. The <m>x</m>-values for these intercepts
      are <m>-2</m> and <m>3</m>. Think about what happens when you subsitutue those numbers into
      the formula for <m>f</m>.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>A graph of <m>y=(x+2)(x-3)</m></caption>
      <image width="60%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}[
                xmin=-4,
                xmax=5,
                ymin=-8,
                ymax=10,
                xtick={-3,-2,...,4},
                minor xtick={-4,-3,...,5},
                ytick={-6,-4,...,8},
                minor ytick={-8,-7,...,10},
                width=0.6\orccaprintwidth
              ]
              \addplot[firstcurve,domain=-3.531:4.531] {x^2-x-6};
              \addplot[color=secondcolor,soliddot] coordinates {(3,0)} node[above left] {$(3,0)$};
              \addplot[color=secondcolor,soliddot] coordinates {(-2,0)} node[above right] {$(-2,0)$};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      So having the factored expression for <m>f</m>, <m>f()=(x+2)(x-3)</m>, can reveal to us
      immediately where the horizontal intercepts are.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Identifying the Greatest Common Factor</title>
    <p>
      The most basic technique for factoring is recognizing the <term>greatest common factor</term>,           <idx><h>G.C.F.</h></idx>
      which is the largest factor that divides into several terms without involving fractions. For             <idx><h>greatest common factor</h></idx>
      example, the greatest common factor between <m>6</m> and <m>8</m> is <m>2</m>, since <m>2</m>
      divides nicely into both <m>6</m> and <m>8</m> and no larger number can do that.
    </p>
    <p>
      Similarly, the greatest common factor between <m>4x</m> and <m>3x^2</m> is <m>x</m>. If you
      write <m>4x</m> as a product of its factors, you have <m>2\cdot 2 \cdot x</m>. And if you
      fully factor <m>3x^2</m>, you have <m>3\cdot x\cdot x</m>. The only factor they have in common
      is <m>x</m>, so that is the greatest common factor. No larger expression goes in nicely to
      both expressions.
    </p>
    <example>
      <title>Finding the Greatest Common Factor</title>
      <p>
        What is the common factor between <m>6x^2</m> and <m>70x</m>? Break down each of these into
        its factors:
        <md>
          <mrow>6x^2 \amp= 2\cdot3\cdot x\cdot x   \amp   70x \amp= 2\cdot5\cdot7\cdot x</mrow>
          <intertext>And identify the common factors:</intertext>
          <mrow>6x^2 \amp= \attention{2}\cdot3\cdot \attention{x}\cdot x   \amp   70x \amp= \attention{2}\cdot5\cdot7\cdot \attention{x}</mrow>
        </md>
        With <m>2</m> and <m>x</m> in common, the greatest common factor is <m>2x</m>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context()->variables->are(x => 'Real', y => 'Real');
        </pg-code>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The greatest common factor between <m>6x</m> and <m>8x</m> is
              <var name="'2x'" width="3"/>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Since <m>6x</m> completely factors as <m>\attention{2}\cdot3\cdot \attention{x}</m>
              <ellipsis/> and <m>8x</m> completely factors as
              <m>\attention{2}\cdot2\cdot2\cdot \attention{x}</m>, <ellipsis/>
            </p>
            <p>
              <ellipsis/> the greatest common factor is <m>2x</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The greatest common factor between <m>14x^2</m> and <m>10x</m> is
              <var name="'2x'" width="3"/>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Since <m>14x^2</m> completely factors as
              <m>\attention{2}\cdot7\cdot \attention{x}\cdot x</m> <ellipsis/> and <m>10x</m>
              completely factors as <m>\attention{2}\cdot5\cdot \attention{x}</m>, <ellipsis/>
            </p>
            <p>
              <ellipsis/> the greatest common factor is <m>2x</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The greatest common factor between <m>6y^2</m> and <m>7y^2</m> is
              <var name="'y^2'" width="3"/>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Since <m>6y^2</m> completely factors as
              <m>2\cdot3\cdot \attention{y}\cdot \attention{y}</m> <ellipsis/> and <m>7y^2</m>
              completely factors as <m>7\cdot\attention{y}\cdot\attention{y}</m>, <ellipsis/>
            </p>
            <p>
              <ellipsis/> the greatest common factor is <m>y^2</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The greatest common factor between <m>12xy^2</m> and <m>9xy</m> is
              <var name="'3xy'" width="3"/>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Since <m>12xy^2</m> completely factors as
              <m>2\cdot2\cdot\attention{3}\cdot \attention{x}\cdot \attention{y}\cdot y</m>
              <ellipsis/> and <m>9xy</m> completely factors as
              <m>\attention{3}\cdot3\cdot \attention{x}\cdot \attention{y}</m>, <ellipsis/>
            </p>
            <p>
              <ellipsis/> the greatest common factor is <m>3xy</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The greatest common factor between <m>6x^3</m>, <m>2x^2</m>, and <m>8x</m> is
              <var name="'2x'" width="3"/>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Since <m>6x^3</m> completely factors as
              <m>\attention{2}\cdot3\cdot \attention{x}\cdot x\cdot x</m> <ellipsis/> <m>2x^2</m>
              completely factors as <m>\attention{2}\cdot\attention{x}\cdot x</m>, <ellipsis/> and
              <m>8x</m> completely factors as <m>\attention{2}\cdot2\cdot2\cdot\attention{x}</m>,
              <ellipsis/>
            </p>
            <p>
              <ellipsis/> the greatest common factor is <m>2x</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Factoring Out the Greatest Common Factor</title>
    <p>
      We have learned the distributive property: <m>a(b+c)=ab+ac</m>. Perhaps you have thought of
      this as a way to <q>distribute</q> the number <m>a</m> to the <m>b</m> and the <m>c</m>. In
      this section, we use the distributive property in the opposite way. If you have an
      expression <m>ab+ac</m>, it is equal to <m>a(b+c)</m>. We say that we <q>factor out</q>
      <m>a</m>, which is the common factor between <m>ab</m> and <m>ac</m>.
    </p>

    <algorithm xml:id="algorithm-factor-gcf">
      <title>Factoring Out the Greatest Common Factor</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Identify the greatest common factor in all terms.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Write the greatest common factor outside a pair of parentheses with appropriate
                addition or subtraction signs inside.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                For each term from the original expression, what would you multiply the greatest
                common factor by to result in that term? Write your answer in the parentheses.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </algorithm>

    <example xml:id="example-factor-gcf">
      <p>
        To factor <m>12x^2+15x</m>:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The greatest common factor of <m>12x^2</m> and <m>15x</m> is <m>3x</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Write some of the answer down, leaving space for terms we will find in a last step:
              <m>3x(\phantom{4x}+\phantom{5})</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>3x(4x+5)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-factor-out-common-factor-trailing-9">
      <p>
        Factor the polynomial <m>3x^3+3x^2-9</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              We identify the greatest common factor as <m>3</m>, because <m>3</m> is the only
              common factor between <m>3x^3</m>, <m>3x^2</m> and <m>9</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              We write: <md>3x^3+3x^2-9=3(\phantom{x^2}+\phantom{x^2}-\phantom{3})</md>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              We ask the question, <m>3</m> times what gives <m>3x^3</m>? The answer is
              <m>x^3</m>. Now we have: <md>3x^3+3x^2-9=3(x^3+\phantom{x^2}-\phantom{3})</md>.
            </p>
            <p>
              We ask the question, <m>3</m> times what gives <m>3x^2</m>? The answer is
              <m>x^2</m>. Now we have: <md>3x^3+3x^2-9=3(x^3+x^2-\phantom{3})</md>.
            </p>
            <p>
              We ask the question, <m>3</m> times what gives <m>9</m>? The answer is <m>3</m>.
              Now we have: <md>3x^3+3x^2-9=3(x^3+x^2-3)</md>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
        To check that this is correct, multiplying through <m>3(x^3+x^2-3)</m> should give the
        original expression <m>3x^3+3x^2-9</m>. We check this, and it does.
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise xml:id="example-factor-out-common-factor-trailing-9x">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Form");
          $answer = Formula("4x(x^2+3x-3)");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Factor the polynomial <m>4x^3+12x^2-12x</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$answer" width="20"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            In this exercise, <m>4x</m> is the greatest common factor. We find
            <md>
              <mrow>4x^3+12x^2-12x\amp=4x(\phantom{x^2}+\phantom{3x}-\phantom{3})</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=4x(x^2+\phantom{3x}-\phantom{3})</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=4x(x^2+3x-\phantom{3})</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=4x(x^2+3x-3)</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            Note that you might fail to recognize that <m>4x</m> is the greatest common factor. At
            first you might only see that, say, <m>4</m> is a common factor. This is OK! You can
            factor out the <m>4</m> and then keep looking for more to factor out:
            <md>
              <mrow>4x^3+12x^2-12x\amp=4(\phantom{x^3}+\phantom{3x^2}-\phantom{3})</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=4(x^3+\phantom{3x^2}-\phantom{3x})</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=4(x^3+3x^2-\phantom{3x})</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=4(x^3+3x^2-3x)</mrow>
            </md>
            Now examine the polynomial that remained in the parentheses. There is <em>still</em> a
            common factor, <m>x</m>. Factoring this out too:
            <md>
              <mrow>\amp=4x(\phantom{x^2}+\phantom{3x}-\phantom{3})</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=4x(x^2+\phantom{3x}-\phantom{3})</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=4x(x^2+3x-\phantom{3})</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=4x(x^2+3x-3)</mrow>
            </md>
            So there is more than one way to find the answer.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Visualizing With Rectangles</title>
    <p>
      You might find it helpful to visualize factoring with a rectangle diagram.
    </p>
    <algorithm>
      <title>Rectangle Diagram Factoring</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Put the terms into adjacent rectangles. Think of these as labeling the areas of each
                rectangle.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Identify the greatest common factor, and mark the height of the overall rectangle
                with it.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Mark the width of each rectangle based on each rectangle's area and height.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Since the overall rectangle's area equals its width times its height, the height is
                one factor, and the sum of the widths is another factor.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </algorithm>

    <example>
      <p>
        We will factor <m>12x^2+15x</m>, the same polynomial from <xref ref="example-factor-gcf"/>,
        so that you can compare the two styles.
      </p>
      <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="0%" valign="bottom">
        <tabular bottom="minor" halign="right">
          <row>
            <cell bottom="none"></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell right="minor" bottom="none"></cell>
            <cell right="minor"><m>12x^2</m></cell>
            <cell right="minor"><m>15x</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
        <tabular bottom="minor" halign="right">
          <row>
            <cell bottom="none"></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell right="minor" bottom="none"><m>3x</m></cell>
            <cell right="minor"><m>12x^2</m></cell>
            <cell right="minor"><m>15x</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
        <tabular bottom="minor" halign="right">
          <row>
            <cell bottom="none"></cell>
            <cell><m>4x</m></cell>
            <cell><m>5</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell right="minor" bottom="none"><m>3x</m></cell>
            <cell right="minor"><m>12x^2</m></cell>
            <cell right="minor"><m>15x</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
        So <m>12x^2+15x</m> factors as <m>3x(4x+5)</m>.
      </p>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>More Examples of Factoring out the Common Factor</title>
    <p>
      Sometimes when factoring out a GCF, there can be a small complication. Here are a few more
      examples to showcase what might come up.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example-negative-leading-coefficient">
      <p>
        Factor <m>-35m^5+5m^4-10m^3</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        First, we identify the common factor. The number <m>5</m> is the greatest common factor of
        the three coefficients (which were <m>-35</m>, <m>5</m>, and <m>-10</m>) and also <m>m^3</m>
        is the largest expression that divides <m>m^5</m>, <m>m^4</m>, and <m>m^3</m>. Therefore the
        greatest common factor is <m>5m^3</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        However, in this example, the leading coefficient, <m>-35</m> is a negative number. When
        this happens, we recommend that you consider that negative sign as part of the greatest
        common factor. So we choose to factor out <m>-5m^3</m>. Note that this causes all of the
        signs to change inside the parentheses.
        <md>
          <mrow>-35m^5\highlight{{}+{}}5m^4\highlight{{}-{}}10m^3\amp=-5m^3(\phantom{7m^2}\highlight{{}-{}}\phantom{m}\highlight{{}+{}}\phantom{2})</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=-5m^3(7m^2-\phantom{m}+\phantom{2})</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=-5m^3(7m^2-m+\phantom{2})</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=-5m^3(7m^2-m+2)</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        It's not wrong to leave the signs alone, but it will make it harder to use factoring in the
        future for the things we use it for.
      </p>
    </example>

    <example>
      <p>
        Factor <m>14-7n^2+28n^4-21n</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice that the terms are not in the standard order where the powers of <m>n</m> decrease as
        you read left to right. It's usually best practice to rearrange the terms into standard
        order first.
        <md>
          14-7n^2+28n^4-21n=28n^4-7n^2-21n+14
        </md>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now this is like earlier examples. The number <m>7</m> divides all of the numerical
        coefficients. And no power of <m>n</m> is a factor of the last term. So the greatest common
        factor is just <m>7</m>. We proceed by factoring that out:
        <md>
          <mrow>14-7n^2+28n^4-21n\amp=28n^4-7n^2-21n+14</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=7\mathopen{}\left(4n^4-n^2-3n+2\right)\mathclose{}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>

    <example>
      <p>
        Factor <m>4m^2-3</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        There are no common factors in those two terms (unless you want to count <m>1</m> or
        <m>-1</m>, but we do not count these for the purposes of identifying a greatest common
        factor). In this situation we can say the polynomial is <term>prime</term> or                         <idx><h>prime polynomial</h></idx>
        <term>irreducible</term>, and leave it as it is.                                                      <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>prime</h></idx>        
      </p>
    </example>

    <example>
      <p>
        Factor <m>-x^3+2x+18</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        There are no common factors in those three terms, and it would be correct to state that this
        polynomial is prime or irreducible. However, since its leading coefficient is negative, it
        may be wise to factor out a negative sign. So, it could be factored as
        <m>-\mathopen{}\left(x^3-2x-18\right)\mathclose{}</m>. Note that <em>every</em> term is
        negated when the leading negative sign is extracted this way.
      </p>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsection-factoring-monic-quadratic-trinomials">
    <title>Factoring Monic Quadratic Trinomials</title>                                                       <idx><h>factoring</h><h>with factor pairs</h></idx>
    <p>
      A trinomial like <m>x^2+5x+6</m> is a <q>monic, quadratic trinomial</q>. It's a
      <q>trinomial</q> because it has three terms. It is <q>quadratic</q> because the highest degree
      term is degree <m>2</m>. And it's <q>monic</q> because the leading coefficient (the number
      being multiplied by <m>x^2</m>) is <m>1</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      When a a polynomial is a monic, quadratic trinomial, it doesn't have a greatest common factor,
      and yet it <em>might</em> be factorable. In this case, <m>x^2+5x+6</m> can be factored as
      <m>(x+2)(x+3)</m>. Now we will learn a process for factoring polynomials like this one.
    </p>

    <p>
      Consider the example <m>x^2+\firsthighlight{5}x+\secondhighlight{6}=(x+2)(x+3)</m>. There are
      at least three things that are important to notice:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The leading coefficient is <m>1</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The two factors on the right use the numbers <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>, and when you
            <em>multiply</em> these you get the <m>\secondhighlight{6}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The two factors on the right use the numbers <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>, and when you
            <em>add</em> these you get the <m>\firsthighlight{5}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      So the idea is that if you need to factor <m>x^2+5x+6</m> and you somehow discover that
      <m>2</m> and <m>3</m> are special numbers (because <m>2\cdot3=6</m> and <m>2+3=5</m>), then
      you can conclude that <m>(x+2)(x+3)</m> is the factored form of the given polynomial.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example-factor-trinomial">
      <p>
        Factor <m>x^2+13x+40</m>. Since the leading coefficient is <m>1</m>, we are looking to write
        this polynomial as <m>(x+\mathord{?})(x+\mathord{?})</m> where the question marks are two
        possibly different, possibly negative, numbers. We need these two numbers to multiply to
        <m>40</m> and add to <m>13</m>. How can you track these two numbers down? Since the numbers
        need to multiply to <m>40</m>, one strategy is to list all <term>factor pairs</term> of
        <m>40</m> in a table just to see what your options are. We'll write down every <em>pair of
        factors</em> that multiply to <m>40</m>.
      </p>

      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
        <tabular>
          <row>
            <cell><m>1\cdot40</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>2\cdot20</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>4\cdot10</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>5\cdot8</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
        <tabular>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-1\cdot(-40)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-2\cdot(-20)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-4\cdot(-10)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-5\cdot(-8)</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        We wanted to find <em>all</em> factor pairs. To avoid missing any, we started using <m>1</m>
        as a factor, and then slowly increased that first factor. The table skips over using
        <m>3</m> as a factor, because <m>3</m> is not a factor of <m>40</m>. Similarly the table
        skips trying <m>6</m> and <m>7</m> as a factor. And there would be no need to continue with
        <m>8</m> and beyond, because we already found <q>large</q> factors like <m>8</m> as the
        partners of <q>small</q> factors like <m>5</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        There is an entire second column where the signs are reversed, since these are also ways to
        multiply two numbers to get <m>40</m>. In the end, there are eight factor pairs.
      </p>

      <p>
        We need a pair of numbers that also <em>adds</em> to <m>13</m>. So we check what each of our
        factor pairs add up to:
      </p>

      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
        <tabular>
          <col right="minor"/>
          <col/>
          <row bottom="minor">
            <cell>Factor Pair</cell>
            <cell>Sum of the Pair</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>1\cdot40</m></cell>
            <cell><m>41</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>2\cdot20</m></cell>
            <cell><m>22</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>4\cdot10</m></cell>
            <cell><m>14</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>5\cdot8</m></cell>
            <cell><m>13</m> (what we wanted)</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>

        <tabular>
          <col right="minor"/>
          <col/>
          <row bottom="minor">
            <cell>Factor Pair</cell>
            <cell>Sum of the Pair</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-1\cdot(-40)</m></cell>
            <cell>(no need to go this far)</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-2\cdot(-20)</m></cell>
            <cell>(no need to go this far)</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-4\cdot(-10)</m></cell>
            <cell>(no need to go this far)</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-5\cdot(-8)</m></cell>
            <cell>(no need to go this far)</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        The winning pair of numbers is <m>5</m> and <m>8</m>. Again, what matters is that
        <m>5\cdot8=40</m>, and <m>5+8=13</m>. So we can conclude that <m>x^2+13x+40=(x+5)(x+8)</m>.
      </p>
    </example>
    <!--TODO: Add several graphs here regarding what factoring might mean -->
    <p>
      To ensure that we made no mistakes, here are some possible checks.
    </p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Multiply it Out</title>
      <p>
        Multiplying out our answer <m>(x+5)(x+8)</m> should give us <m>x^2+13x+40</m>.
      </p>

      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\amp(x+5)(x+8)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=(x+5)\cdot x+(x+5)\cdot8</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=x^2+5x+8x+40</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp\confirm{=}x^2+13x+40</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <stack>
          <p>
            We could also use a rectangle diagram to verify the factorization is correct:
          </p>

          <tabular bottom="minor" halign="center">
            <row>
              <cell bottom="none"></cell>
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>5</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell right="minor" bottom="none"><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>x^2</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>5x</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell right="minor" bottom="none"><m>8</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>8x</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>40</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </stack>
      </sidebyside>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Evaluating</title>
      <p>
        If the formula <m>f(x)=x^2+13x+40</m> really is the same as the formula
        <m>f(x)=(x+5)(x+8)</m>, then evaluating the two formuals at some inputs should give the
        same outputs. With our factored formula, it's clear that <m>f(-5)=0</m> and <m>f(-8)=0</m>.
        What happens if we use the original formula?
        <md>
          <mrow>f(\substitute{-5})\amp\wonder{=}0\amp f(\substitute{-8})\amp\wonder{=}0</mrow>
          <mrow>(\substitute{-5})^2+13(\substitute{-5})+40\amp\wonder{=}0\amp(\substitute{-8})^2+13(\substitute{-8})+40\amp\wonder{=}0</mrow>
          <mrow>25-65+40\amp\wonder{=}0\amp 64-104+40\amp\wonder{=}0</mrow>
          <mrow>0\amp\confirm{=}0\amp 0\amp\confirm{=}0</mrow>
        </md>.
        This also gives us evidence that the factoring was correct.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>y^2-11y+24</m>. The negative coefficient on the middle term introduces aa small
          complication, but the process is really the same.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We need a pair of numbers that multiply to <m>24</m> and add to <m>-11</m>. Note that we
          will track that the mystery numbers need to add to a <em>negative</em> total.
        </p>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
          <tabular>
            <col right="minor"/>
            <col/>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell>Factor Pair</cell>
              <cell>Sum of the Pair</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>1\cdot24</m></cell>
              <cell><m>25</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>2\cdot12</m></cell>
              <cell><m>14</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>3\cdot8</m></cell>
              <cell><m>11</m> (close; wrong sign)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>4\cdot6</m></cell>
              <cell><m>10</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

          <tabular>
            <col right="minor"/>
            <col/>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell>Factor Pair</cell>
              <cell>Sum of the Pair</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-1\cdot(-24)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-25</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-2\cdot(-12)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-14</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-3\cdot(-8)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-11</m> (what we wanted)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-4\cdot(-6)</m></cell>
              <cell>(no need to go this far)</cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          So <m>y^2-11y+24=(y-3)(y-8)</m>. To confirm that this is correct, we should check. Either
          by multiplying out the factored form:
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>(y-3)(y-8)\amp=(y-3)\cdot y-(y-3)\cdot8</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=y^2-3y-8y+24</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp\confirm{=}y^2-11y+24</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <tabular bottom="minor" halign="center">
            <row>
              <cell bottom="none"></cell>
              <cell><m>y</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell right="minor" bottom="none"><m>y</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>y^2</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>-3y</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell right="minor" bottom="none"><m>-8</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>-8y</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>24</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          Or by evaluating the original expression at <m>\substitute{3}</m> and
          <m>\substitute{8}</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>\substitute{3}^2-11(\substitute{3})+24\amp\wonder{=}0\amp\substitute{8}^2-11(\substitute{8})+24\amp\wonder{=}0</mrow>
            <mrow>9-33+24\amp\wonder{=}0\amp 64-88+24\amp\wonder{=}0</mrow>
            <mrow>0\amp\confirm{=}0\amp 0\amp\confirm{=}0</mrow>
          </md>.
          Our factorization passes the tests.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>z^2+5z-6</m>. We have another negative coefficient, this time in the last term.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We need a pair of numbers that multiply to <m>-6</m> and add to <m>5</m>. We will track
          that the mystery numbers need to multiply to a <em>negative</em> product.
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
          <tabular>
            <col right="minor"/>
            <col/>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell>Factor Pair</cell>
              <cell>Sum of the Pair</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>1\cdot(-6)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-5</m> (close; wrong sign)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>2\cdot(-3)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>14</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

          <tabular>
            <col right="minor"/>
            <col/>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell>Factor Pair</cell>
              <cell>Sum of the Pair</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-1\cdot6</m></cell>
              <cell><m>5</m> (what we wanted)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-2\cdot3</m></cell>
              <cell>(no need to go this far)</cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          So <m>z^2+5z-6=(z-1)(z+6)</m>. To confirm that this is correct, we should check. Either
          by multiplying out the factored form:
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>(z-1)(z+6)\amp=(z-1)\cdot z+(z-1)\cdot6</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=z^2-z+6z-6</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp\confirm{=}z^2+5z-6</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <tabular bottom="minor" halign="center">
            <row>
              <cell bottom="none"></cell>
              <cell><m>z</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell right="minor" bottom="none"><m>z</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>z^2</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>-z</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell right="minor" bottom="none"><m>6</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>6z</m></cell>
              <cell right="minor"><m>-6</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          Or by evaluating the original expression at <m>\substitute{1}</m> and
          <m>\substitute{-6}</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>\substitute{1}^2+5(\substitute{1})-6\amp\wonder{=}0\amp(\substitute{-6})^2+5(\substitute{-6})-6\amp\wonder{=}0</mrow>
            <mrow>1+5-6\amp\wonder{=}0\amp 36-30-6\amp\wonder{=}0</mrow>
            <mrow>0\amp\confirm{=}0\amp 0\amp\confirm{=}0</mrow>
          </md>.
          Our factorization passes the tests.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Form");
          Context()->variables->are(m => 'Real');
          $answer = Formula("(m+4)(m-10)");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Factor <m>m^2-6m-40</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$answer" width="25"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We need a pair of numbers that multiply to <m>-40</m> and add to <m>-6</m>.
          </p>

          <tabular>
            <col right="minor"/>
            <col/>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell>Factor Pair</cell>
              <cell>Sum of the Pair</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>1\cdot(-40)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-39</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>2\cdot(-20)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-18</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>4\cdot(-10)</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-6</m> (what we wanted)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>(no need to continue)</cell>
              <cell>...</cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

          <p>
            So <m>m^2-6m-40=(m+4)(m-10)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Factoring in Stages</title>                                                                        <idx><h>factoring</h><h>in stages</h></idx>
    <p>
      Sometimes factoring a polynomial will take two or more <q>stages.</q> Always begin factoring a
      polynomial by factoring out its greatest common factor, and <em>then</em> look to see if the
      remaining polynomial in the parentheses can be factored more using another strategy. The
      process of factoring a polynomial is not complete until <em>each</em> of the factors can't be
      factored further.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>2z^2-6z-80</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We first factor out the common factor, <m>2</m>:
          <md>
            2z^2-6z-80=2\left(z^2-3z-40\right)
          </md>
          Now we are left with a factored expression that might factor more. Looking inside the
          parentheses, what two numbers multiply to be <m>-40</m> and add to be <m>-3</m>? Since
          <m>5</m> and <m>-8</m> do the job, the full factorization is:
          <md>
            <mrow>2z^2-6z-80\amp=2\left(z^2-3z-40\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2(z+5)(z-8)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>-r^2+2r+24</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The three terms don't exactly have a common factor, but as discussed in
          <xref ref="example-negative-leading-coefficient"/>, when the leading term has a negative
          sign, we recommend that you factor out that negative sign:
          <md>
            -r^2+2r+24=-\mathopen{}\left(r^2-2r-24\right)\mathclose{}
          </md>.
          Looking inside the parentheses, what two numbers multiply to make <m>-24</m> and add to
          make <m>-2</m>? Since <m>-6</m> and <m>4</m> work here and the full factorization is
          shown:
          <md>
            <mrow>-r^2+2r+24\amp=-\mathopen{}\left(r^2-2r-24\right)\mathclose{}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-(r-6)(r+4)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Difference of Squares</title>                                                                      <idx><h>factoring</h><h>difference of squares</h></idx>
    <p>
      If <m>b</m> is some positive integer, then when you multiply <m>(x-b)(x+b)</m>:
      <md>
        <mrow>(x-b)(x+b)\amp=x^2-bx+bx-b^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=x^2-b^2</mrow>
      </md>.
      The <m>-bx</m> and the <m>+bx</m> cancel each other out. So this is telling us that
      <md>
        x^2-b^2=(x-b)(x+b)
      </md>.
      And so if we ever encounter a polynomial of the form <m>x^2-b^2</m> (a <q>difference of
      squares</q>) then we have a quick formula for factoring it. Just identify what <q><m>b</m></q>
      is, and use that in <m>(x-b)(x+b)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      To use this formula, it's important to recognize which numbers are perfect squares, as in
      <xref ref="figure-perfect-squares"/>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-perfect-squares">
      <caption>Multiplication table with squares</caption>
      <tabular top="major" bottom="minor" left="major" right="minor" halign="center">
        <col right="medium" />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col />
        <col right="major"/>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell><m>\times</m></cell>
          <cell><m>1</m></cell>
          <cell><m>2</m></cell>
          <cell><m>3</m></cell>
          <cell><m>4</m></cell>
          <cell><m>5</m></cell>
          <cell><m>6</m></cell>
          <cell><m>7</m></cell>
          <cell><m>8</m></cell>
          <cell><m>9</m></cell>
          <cell><m>10</m></cell>
          <cell><m>11</m></cell>
          <cell><m>12</m></cell>
          <cell><m>13</m></cell>
          <cell><m>14</m></cell>
          <cell><m>15</m></cell>
          <cell><m>16</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>1</m></cell>
          <cell><m>1</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{2}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{3}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{4}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{5}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{6}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{7}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{8}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{9}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{10}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{11}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{12}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{13}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{14}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{15}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{16}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>2</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{2}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>4</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{6}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{8}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{10}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{12}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{14}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{16}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{18}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{20}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{22}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{24}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{26}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{28}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{30}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{32}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>3</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{3}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{6}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>9</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{12}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{15}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{18}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{21}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{24}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{27}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{30}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{33}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{36}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{39}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{42}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{45}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{48}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>4</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{4}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{8}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{12}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>16</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{20}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{24}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{28}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{32}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{36}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{40}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{44}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{48}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{52}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{56}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{60}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{64}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>5</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{5}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{10}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{15}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{20}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>25</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{30}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{35}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{40}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{45}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{50}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{55}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{60}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{65}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{70}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{75}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{80}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>6</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{6}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{12}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{18}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{24}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{30}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>36</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{42}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{48}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{54}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{60}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{66}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{72}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{78}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{84}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{90}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{96}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>7</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{7}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\lowlight{14}</m></cell>
